documents.title: Create Your First Agent
documents.text: Learn how to create and start an AI coding agent from the dashboard

documents.title: Click the + button
documents.text: In the left sidebar, click the + (plus) button at the top to open the Create Agent dialog.

documents.title: Enter agent name
documents.text: Give your agent a descriptive name like "backend-api" or "frontend-ui". Use lowercase letters, numbers, hyphens, or underscores.

documents.title: Set working directory (optional)
documents.text: Enter the project path where this agent will work. For example: ~/projects/my-app. Leave empty to set later.

documents.title: Click Create Agent
documents.text: Click the "Create Agent" button. AI Maestro will create a tmux session and start your AI coding tool automatically.

documents.title: Start working
documents.text: Your new agent appears in the sidebar. Click it to see the terminal view and start interacting with your AI assistant.

documents.title: View Agent Profile
documents.text: See agent details, stats, and configuration options

documents.title: Select an agent
documents.text: Click on any agent in the left sidebar to select it.

documents.title: Open the profile
documents.text: Click on the agent's name at the top of the main panel, or click the gear icon next to it.

documents.title: View agent information
documents.text: The profile shows the agent's name, working directory, creation date, and current status.

documents.title: Check statistics
documents.text: See metrics like total conversations, indexed documents, and graph nodes for this agent.

documents.title: Manage the agent
documents.text: From the profile, you can rename the agent, change its working directory, hibernate it, or delete it.

documents.title: Hibernate & Wake Agents
documents.text: Save resources by hibernating inactive agents

documents.title: Find an active agent
documents.text: In the sidebar, look for agents with a green "Online" status indicator.

documents.title: Open agent profile
documents.text: Click the agent's name or gear icon to open its profile panel.

documents.title: Click Hibernate
documents.text: In the profile, click the "Hibernate" button. This saves the agent's state and closes its tmux session.

documents.title: Agent shows as Hibernated
documents.text: Hibernated agents show a moon icon and "Hibernated" status. They preserve all memory and settings.

documents.title: Wake the agent
documents.text: To resume, click on the hibernated agent and click the "Wake" button. A new session starts with all context restored.

documents.title: Distributed AI Agents
documents.text: Understanding how AI agents run across multiple machines

documents.title: What are distributed AI agents?
documents.text: AI Maestro enables you to run AI coding agents across multiple computers. Each machine (host) can run its own agents, and you can manage them all from a single dashboard. This is distributed AI computing - spreading intelligent work across your infrastructure.

documents.title: Why distribute agents?
documents.text: Different projects may live on different machines. A backend API might be on a server, while frontend code is on your laptop. With distributed agents, each agent works where its code lives, with full local file access and native performance.

documents.title: The host network
documents.text: Each computer running AI Maestro is a "host". Hosts discover and connect to each other automatically on your local network. You can also manually add remote hosts by their URL in Settings.

documents.title: Agents have memory
documents.text: Each agent maintains its own memory - conversation history, indexed code graphs, and learned context. This memory travels with the agent, even when transferred between hosts.

documents.title: Agent collaboration
documents.text: Agents can send messages to each other across hosts. A frontend agent can ask a backend agent about API endpoints. An architect agent can coordinate work between specialized agents.

documents.title: Transfer and migrate
documents.text: Need to move an agent to a more powerful machine? Transfer it. The agent's entire state - memory, settings, and indexed data - moves to the new host. Resume exactly where you left off.

documents.title: How Agents Work
documents.text: The technical architecture behind AI Maestro agents

documents.title: Agents run in tmux sessions
documents.text: Each agent runs inside a tmux terminal session. This means agents persist even if you close the dashboard. They can run long tasks, and you can reconnect anytime to see their progress.

documents.title: The subconscious process
documents.text: Behind each agent is a "subconscious" - a background process that indexes conversations, builds code graphs, and maintains searchable memory. This runs locally on the same machine as the agent.

documents.title: Local-first design
documents.text: AI Maestro is designed for local-first operation. Your code never leaves your machines. Agents read and write files directly, with no cloud intermediary. This means faster operations and complete privacy.

documents.title: Skills extend capabilities
documents.text: Agents gain abilities through "skills" - modular capabilities like messaging, memory search, graph queries, and documentation search. These are installed automatically during setup.

documents.title: The dashboard is a window
documents.text: The AI Maestro web dashboard is just a view into your agents. Agents continue running whether you're watching or not. The dashboard connects to agents via WebSocket for real-time terminal streaming.

documents.title: Send Messages Between Agents
documents.text: Enable your agents to communicate and collaborate asynchronously

documents.title: Select an agent
documents.text: Click on an agent in the left sidebar to select it. This will be the agent whose messages you view.

documents.title: Open the Messages tab
documents.text: In the main panel, click the "Messages" tab (envelope icon) to open the Message Center.

documents.title: View inbox and sent messages
documents.text: The Message Center shows your inbox with received messages and a sent folder. Unread messages are highlighted.

documents.title: Read a message
documents.text: Click on any message to expand and read its full content. Messages are automatically marked as read.

documents.title: How agents send messages
documents.text: Agents send messages through conversation. With the messaging skill, an agent can say "send a message to backend-api about the API changes" and it will be delivered.

documents.title: Search Agent Memory
documents.text: Search through past conversations to find context and decisions

documents.title: Select an agent
documents.text: Click on the agent whose conversation history you want to search in the left sidebar.

documents.title: Open the Chat tab
documents.text: Click the "Chat" tab (message bubble icon) to access the conversation history and search.

documents.title: Use the search box
documents.text: At the top of the Chat panel, you'll find a search box. Type your query to search across all conversations.

documents.title: Browse results
documents.text: Search results show matching conversation snippets with timestamps. Click any result to see the full context.

documents.title: Filter by date or topic
documents.text: Use the filters to narrow down results by date range or conversation topic. This helps find specific decisions or discussions.

documents.title: Explore Code Graph
documents.text: Visualize code relationships, dependencies, and call paths

documents.title: Select an agent with a project
documents.text: Click on an agent that has a working directory set. The code graph is built from the agent's project files.

documents.title: Open the Graph tab
documents.text: Click the "Graph" tab (network icon) in the main panel to open the code graph explorer.

documents.title: Browse the visualization
documents.text: The graph shows your codebase structure - functions, classes, and their relationships as connected nodes.

documents.title: Click on nodes
documents.text: Click any node to see details about that component - its type, location, and connections to other code.

documents.title: Find relationships
documents.text: Hover over nodes to highlight their connections. This helps you understand what calls what and how components relate.

documents.title: Search components
documents.text: Use the search box to find specific functions, classes, or files. The graph will focus on matching nodes.

documents.title: Search Documentation
documents.text: Find answers in indexed documentation, READMEs, and API docs

documents.title: Ensure docs are indexed
documents.text: The docs search skill indexes documentation files in your project. This happens automatically when an agent works in a project.

documents.title: Ask your agent
documents.text: Simply ask your agent questions about documentation. For example: "Search the docs for authentication" or "What does the API say about rate limits?"

documents.title: Review search results
documents.text: The agent will search through indexed documentation and return relevant snippets with source file references.

documents.title: Supported file types
documents.text: Docs search indexes README files, Markdown documentation, API specs, and code comments from your project.

documents.title: Refine your search
documents.text: If results aren't what you need, try rephrasing your question or being more specific about the topic.

documents.title: Add Remote Hosts
documents.text: Connect to AI Maestro instances on other machines

documents.title: Open Settings
documents.text: Click the Settings link at the bottom of the left sidebar to open the Settings page.

documents.title: Go to Hosts section
documents.text: In Settings, find the "Hosts" section. You'll see your local host listed with its status.

documents.title: Click Add Host
documents.text: Click the "Add Host" button to open the connection dialog.

documents.title: Enter the host URL
documents.text: Enter the remote AI Maestro URL. For example: http://192.168.1.50:23000 or http://my-macbook.local:23000

documents.title: Verify connection
documents.text: After adding, the host card will show "Online" with a green dot if connected successfully. Red means connection failed.

documents.title: View remote agents
documents.text: Remote agents now appear in your sidebar with a host badge. Click them to view and interact just like local agents.

documents.title: Transfer Agent to Another Host
documents.text: Move agents between machines while preserving their memory

documents.title: Ensure remote host is connected
documents.text: Before transferring, make sure the destination host is added in Settings > Hosts and shows as "Online". See "Add Remote Hosts" tutorial first.

documents.title: Open agent profile
documents.text: Click on the agent you want to transfer in the sidebar. Then click the agent's name or the gear icon to open its profile panel.

documents.title: Find the Transfer button
documents.text: In the agent profile, look for the "Transfer to Another Host" button (arrow icon) near the top of the panel.

documents.title: Select destination host
documents.text: Click the Transfer button to open the dialog. Choose your destination host from the dropdown list.

documents.title: Confirm and transfer
documents.text: Review the transfer details and click "Transfer". The agent's memory, graph data, and settings will be packaged and sent.

documents.title: Activate on new host
documents.text: The agent will appear on the destination host. Click "Wake" or create a session to start using it there.

documents.title: Access from Mobile Devices
documents.text: View and manage agents from your phone or tablet

documents.title: Install Tailscale
documents.text: Tailscale is a free VPN that creates a secure network between your devices. Install it on your computer (where AI Maestro runs) and on your phone/tablet.

documents.title: Sign in to Tailscale
documents.text: Open Tailscale on both devices and sign in with the same account. Your devices will automatically connect to your private Tailscale network.

documents.title: Get your computer's Tailscale IP
documents.text: On your computer, run "tailscale ip -4" in terminal. You'll get an IP like 100.x.x.x. This is your Tailscale IP that works from anywhere.

documents.title: Access from mobile
documents.text: On your phone/tablet browser, go to http://100.x.x.x:23000 (using the Tailscale IP from step 3). You'll see the AI Maestro dashboard.

documents.title: Works from anywhere
documents.text: Tailscale works over the internet too. Whether you're at home, at a coffee shop, or traveling - if both devices have Tailscale running, you can access your agents.

documents.title: Common Issues & Fixes
documents.text: Solutions to the most common problems users encounter

documents.title: Agent not appearing in sidebar
documents.text: If your agent doesn't show up: 1) Wait 10 seconds for auto-refresh, 2) Click the refresh button in the sidebar, 3) Refresh the browser page. If still missing, verify the agent is running with "tmux list-sessions" in terminal.

documents.title: WebSocket connection error
documents.text: If you see connection errors: 1) Check if AI Maestro is running (should be at http://localhost:23000), 2) Refresh the browser page, 3) Check if port 23000 is in use by another app. Try "lsof -i :23000" to see what's using the port.

documents.title: Terminal shows blank screen
documents.text: If the terminal is blank when you click an agent: 1) Click directly in the terminal area to focus it, 2) Refresh the browser page, 3) The agent may have exited - try restarting it from the sidebar menu.

documents.title: AI Maestro won't start
documents.text: If the application won't start: 1) Check if another process is using port 23000, 2) Run "yarn dev" or check PM2 logs with "pm2 logs ai-maestro", 3) Verify Node.js is installed with "node --version".

documents.title: Services not working after restart
documents.text: After restarting your computer, AI Maestro and tmux don't auto-start. You need to: 1) Open Terminal and run "tmux new-session -d" to start tmux, 2) Navigate to AI Maestro folder and run "yarn dev" or "pm2 start ai-maestro".

documents.title: Getting more help
documents.text: If these solutions don't work: Check the full troubleshooting guide in the docs folder, or visit GitHub Issues at github.com/23blocks-OS/ai-maestro/issues to report a problem.

documents.title: Terminal Scrolling Guide
documents.text: How to scroll and navigate in the terminal view

documents.title: Why scrolling seems limited
documents.text: When Claude Code is running, it uses an "alternate screen" - a separate display area. This is normal behavior for full-screen terminal apps. Your shell history is still there, just hidden.

documents.title: Enable mouse scrolling (recommended)
documents.text: Run our setup script: "./scripts/setup-tmux.sh" or add "set -g mouse on" to your ~/.tmux.conf file. Then reload with "tmux source-file ~/.tmux.conf". Now mouse wheel scrolling works!

documents.title: Use keyboard shortcuts
documents.text: In the browser terminal: Shift+PageUp/PageDown scrolls by page, Shift+Arrow Up/Down scrolls 5 lines. These work for the visible buffer before Claude enters alternate screen.

documents.title: Use tmux copy mode
documents.text: Press Ctrl+B then [ to enter copy mode. Use arrow keys or PageUp/PageDown to scroll. Press "q" to exit. This accesses the full tmux scrollback history.

documents.title: Increase scrollback buffer
documents.text: Add "set -g history-limit 50000" to your ~/.tmux.conf to save more history. This gives you 50,000 lines of scrollback in tmux copy mode.

documents.title: Fix Git & SSH Errors
documents.text: Resolve "Permission denied (publickey)" errors in agent sessions

documents.title: Why SSH fails in agents
documents.text: After restarting your computer, SSH agent sockets change paths. Agent sessions (tmux) don't automatically get the new path, so git operations fail with "Permission denied (publickey)".

documents.title: Quick fix for current session
documents.text: In the agent's terminal, type: exec $SHELL and press Enter. This restarts the shell and picks up the correct SSH configuration. Then try your git command again.

documents.title: Set up permanent fix
documents.text: Add this to your ~/.zshrc (or ~/.bashrc): if [ -S "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ] && [ ! -h "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ]; then mkdir -p ~/.ssh && ln -sf "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ~/.ssh/ssh_auth_sock; fi

documents.title: Configure tmux for SSH
documents.text: Add to ~/.tmux.conf: set-environment -g 'SSH_AUTH_SOCK' ~/.ssh/ssh_auth_sock. Then run "tmux source-file ~/.tmux.conf" to apply.

documents.title: Verify it works
documents.text: Run "ssh -T git@github.com" or "ssh -T git@gitlab.com" in your agent. If you see a welcome message, SSH is working. If not, check that your SSH keys are loaded with "ssh-add -l".

documents.title: macOS Network Privacy Fix
documents.text: Fix "connection refused" errors when connecting remote hosts on macOS 15+

documents.title: The problem
documents.text: macOS 15 (Sequoia) introduced Local Network Privacy protection. This can block AI Maestro from connecting to other machines on your network, showing "connection refused" or timeout errors.

documents.title: Check if this affects you
documents.text: If you can access http://localhost:23000 but cannot connect to remote hosts (like http://192.168.1.x:23000), Local Network Privacy may be blocking the connection.

documents.title: Grant Terminal network access
documents.text: Open System Settings > Privacy & Security > Local Network. Find "Terminal" (or your terminal app) and toggle it ON. This allows terminal apps to access devices on your network.

documents.title: Alternative: Use Tailscale
documents.text: Tailscale VPN bypasses Local Network Privacy entirely. Install Tailscale on both machines, and connect using Tailscale IPs (100.x.x.x) instead of local network IPs.

documents.title: Verify the fix
documents.text: Try connecting to your remote host again via Settings > Add Host. If using Tailscale, use the Tailscale IP instead of local IP.

documents.title: Distributed AI Computing
documents.text: Running AI coding agents across multiple machines in your infrastructure. Each computer (host) runs its own agents locally, while a central dashboard lets you manage and coordinate them all. Agents work where the code lives, with full local file access.

documents.title: Agent
documents.text: An AI coding assistant that runs in its own tmux session. Each agent has its own memory, working directory, and can communicate with other agents. Agents persist their state even when hibernated.

documents.title: Local-First
documents.text: AI Maestro's design philosophy where all code and data stay on your machines. Agents read and write files directly with no cloud intermediary. This ensures privacy, speed, and works offline.

documents.title: Subconscious
documents.text: A background process that runs alongside each agent. It indexes conversations, builds code graphs, and maintains searchable memory. The subconscious runs locally on the same machine as the agent.

documents.title: Session
documents.text: A tmux terminal session where an agent runs. Sessions contain the active terminal, command history, and current state of the AI assistant. Multiple agents can run in parallel sessions.

documents.title: Host
documents.text: A machine running AI Maestro. The local host is your current computer. Remote hosts are other machines you can connect to, allowing you to manage agents across multiple computers from one dashboard.

documents.title: Working Directory
documents.text: The folder path where an agent operates. This is typically your project folder. The agent will read and modify files within this directory when you give it coding tasks.

documents.title: Hibernation
documents.text: A power-saving state for agents. When hibernated, an agent's tmux session is closed but all memory and settings are preserved. Wake the agent to resume work exactly where you left off.

documents.title: Wake
documents.text: Bringing a hibernated agent back online. When you wake an agent, a new tmux session is created and the AI assistant starts with all previous memory and context restored.

documents.title: Memory Search
documents.text: A tool that searches through an agent's conversation history. Use it to find past discussions, decisions, or context from previous coding sessions. Helps agents remember what was discussed.

documents.title: Graph Query
documents.text: A tool that visualizes and searches code relationships. The code graph shows how functions, classes, and files connect to each other. Useful for understanding complex codebases.

documents.title: Docs Search
documents.text: A tool that searches through indexed documentation files in your project. Agents can query README files, API docs, Markdown documentation, and code comments to find answers about libraries, frameworks, and project-specific information.

documents.title: Messaging
documents.text: The system that allows agents to send messages to each other. Messages are asynchronous - an agent can send a message and continue working while waiting for a reply.

documents.title: Inbox
documents.text: Where an agent receives messages from other agents. Check the Messages tab to see unread messages. Messages contain requests, updates, or information from collaborating agents.

documents.title: Message Center
documents.text: The interface for viewing and managing agent messages. Shows both inbox (received) and sent messages. Access it via the Messages tab when viewing an agent.

documents.title: tmux
documents.text: A terminal multiplexer that runs in the background. AI Maestro uses tmux to manage agent sessions. Each agent gets its own tmux session that persists even if the dashboard is closed.

documents.title: Claude Code
documents.text: The AI coding assistant that powers each agent. Claude Code can read and write files, run commands, search code, and help with programming tasks. It runs inside a tmux session.

documents.title: Terminal
documents.text: The command-line interface where agents run. The terminal view in AI Maestro shows the live output from the agent's tmux session. You can type commands and see AI responses here.

documents.title: Immersive Mode
documents.text: A full-screen terminal experience. Click "Immersive Experience" to focus on a single agent's terminal without the sidebar or other distractions. Great for deep coding sessions.

documents.title: Transfer
documents.text: Moving an agent from one host to another. When you transfer an agent, all its memory, graph data, and settings are packaged and sent to the destination machine.

documents.title: Remote Host
documents.text: Another computer running AI Maestro that you connect to from your dashboard. Add remote hosts in Settings to manage agents across multiple machines from a single interface.

documents.title: Sidebar
documents.text: The left panel showing all your agents organized by category. Click agents to switch between them. The + button creates new agents. Collapse it with the menu button for more space.

documents.title: Dashboard
documents.text: The main AI Maestro interface. Shows your agents in the sidebar, the active agent's terminal, and tabs for Messages, Chat history, and Graph views.

documents.title: Status
documents.text: An agent's current state. "Online" means the agent is running in an active session. "Hibernated" means the session is paused but memory is preserved. "Offline" means the session ended.

documents.title: Skills
documents.text: Abilities installed on agents that extend their capabilities. Skills include messaging, memory search, graph query, and docs search. Install skills to give agents new powers.

documents.title: Profile
documents.text: An agent's configuration page showing its name, working directory, creation date, and statistics. Access it by clicking the agent's name or the gear icon. Manage or rename agents here.

documents.title: Collaboration
documents.text: When multiple agents work together on a project. Agents can send messages to each other, share context, and divide tasks. Each agent focuses on its specialty while coordinating with others.

documents.title: Alternate Screen
documents.text: A separate display buffer used by full-screen apps like Claude Code. When you scroll but see shell history instead of Claude output, this is why. Use tmux copy mode (Ctrl+B, [) to scroll the alternate screen.

documents.title: Copy Mode
documents.text: A tmux feature for scrolling and selecting text. Enter with Ctrl+B then [. Use arrow keys or PageUp/Down to scroll. Press q to exit. Essential for viewing history when Claude Code is running.

documents.title: WebSocket
documents.text: The connection technology between your browser and AI Maestro. If you see connection errors, the WebSocket may have dropped. Refresh the page to reconnect. Agents keep running even if the connection drops.

documents.title: Port
documents.text: AI Maestro runs on port 23000 by default (http://localhost:23000). If you get "port in use" errors, another app is using that port. Find it with "lsof -i :23000" and close it, or use a different port.

documents.title: WSL2
documents.text: Windows Subsystem for Linux version 2 - Microsoft's solution for running Linux tools on Windows. AI Maestro requires WSL2 on Windows because tmux is a Linux tool. Install with "wsl --install" in PowerShell.

documents.title: Tailscale
documents.text: A free VPN service that creates a secure private network between your devices. Use Tailscale to access AI Maestro from mobile devices, other computers, or when traveling. Works from anywhere with internet.

documents.title: PM2
documents.text: A process manager that keeps AI Maestro running in the background. Restart with "pm2 restart ai-maestro", check status with "pm2 status", and view logs with "pm2 logs ai-maestro".

documents.title: Local Network Privacy
documents.text: A macOS 15+ security feature that can block apps from accessing other devices on your network. If remote hosts show "connection refused", go to System Settings > Privacy & Security > Local Network and enable access for Terminal.
